    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/card/10_1186_s13321_022_00613_8__task_003/scope_drift",
      "@type": "asbval:ScopeDriftAssertion",
      "asbval:drift_notes": [
        "The card title 'Reconstruct the Bayesian meta-learning RT projection module' is narrower than the full paper scope, which includes both RT prediction (DNN models) and projection (meta-learning). The card focuses only on the projection component.",
        "The card does not mention the RT prediction step (DNN training on SMRT dataset), which is a major component of the paper's workflow (Fig. 2, steps 1-2). The projection module alone cannot function without pre-trained RT predictions.",
        "The card lists only 'alvaDesc' as a tool, but the paper uses many other tools: XGBoost, LightGBM, CatBoost, deep neural networks, Gaussian Processes, and various kernel methods. However, alvaDesc is the only tool used for feature generation (molecular descriptors/fingerprints), which is the input to the projection module."
      ],
      "asbval:n_drift_notes": 3,
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "task_003",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "card",
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T12:54:43.338302+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/card/10_1186_s13321_022_00613_8__task_004/000",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "To study the robustness of the projection method when only a few metabolites are known, the number of training points was varied between 10 and 50... When using as few as 10 training points, the global performance decreases to 68%... Table 5 shows that, when using 50 training points, our projection method ranks the correct identity among the top three candidates in 70% of the cases... When decreasing the number of training points to just 10 samples, the percentage is 68%",
      "asbval:note": "The paper explicitly tests meta-learning with 10 training points and reports competitive performance (68% ranking accuracy vs 70% with 50 points), directly addressing the research question.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-s13321-022-00613-8",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "task_004",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "card",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Can a Bayesian meta-learning approach achieve competitive retention time prediction error rates when calibrated with only 10 molecules across different chromatographic methods?",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T12:55:04.937766+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/card/10_1186_s13321_022_00613_8__task_004/001",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Table 4 shows these three metrics and the median relative error (in %) for the meta-learned GP... Figures 7 and 8 show the MAE and scaled interval scores for the projections to four CMs from the PredRet database when using different models. MEDAE results show a similar behaviour to those obtained with MAE... Table 5 shows the percentage of the results where, using the Retention Time (RT) projection function, the true molecule was ranked among the top three candidates",
      "asbval:note": "Paper provides Table 4 with MAE, MEDAE, and scaled interval scores for meta-learned GPs at 10 training points, and Figures 7-8 comparing against baseline methods (GAM, RLM, PLM).",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-s13321-022-00613-8",
