    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/metabolite-candidate-ranking-likelihood-scoring/004",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "To project retention times between chromatographic methods, a novel Bayesian meta-learning approach that can learn from just a few molecules is proposed.",
      "asbval:note": "Core methodological contribution explicitly described.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-s13321-022-00613-8",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "metabolite-candidate-ranking-likelihood-scoring",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "methods",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Bayesian meta-learning approach to project retention times between chromatographic methods",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T12:59:28.051672+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/metabolite-candidate-ranking-likelihood-scoring/005",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "By applying this projection between the deep neural network retention time predictions and a given chromatographic method, our approach can be integrated into a metabolite annotation workflow to obtain z-scores for the candidate annotations. The use of z-scores permits considering the uncertainty in the projection when ranking candidates, and not only the accuracy.",
      "asbval:note": "z-scores are explicitly generated to rank candidates while incorporating uncertainty.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-s13321-022-00613-8",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "metabolite-candidate-ranking-likelihood-scoring",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "expected_outputs",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "z-scores for candidate annotations reflecting both point estimates and prediction confidence",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T12:59:28.051672+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/metabolite-candidate-ranking-likelihood-scoring/006",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "In this scenario, our results show that in 68% of the cases the correct molecule was among the top three candidates filtered by mass and ranked according to z-scores... When using 50 training points, our projection method ranks the correct identity among the top three candidates in 70% of the cases.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper reports 68% with 10 training points and 70% with 50 training points for top-3 ranking accuracy.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-s13321-022-00613-8",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "metabolite-candidate-ranking-likelihood-scoring",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "expected_outputs",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Ranking of candidate metabolites with correct molecule among top three candidates in 68-70% of cases",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T12:59:28.051672+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/metabolite-candidate-ranking-likelihood-scoring/007",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "To the best of our knowledge, these are the most accurate predictions published up to date over the SMRT dataset. To project retention times between chromatographic methods, a novel Bayesian meta-learning approach that can learn from just a few molecules is proposed... it is enough that just as few as 10 molecules of a given experiment have been identified",
      "asbval:note": "Paper explicitly states 10 molecules are sufficient for the meta-learning projection approach.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-s13321-022-00613-8",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "metabolite-candidate-ranking-likelihood-scoring",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "parameters",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Minimum 10 identified molecules needed for meta-learning projection",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T12:59:28.051672+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/metabolite-candidate-ranking-likelihood-scoring/008",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "We have trained state-of-the-art machine learning regressors using the 80, 038 experimental retention times from the METLIN Small Molecule Retention Tim (SMRT) dataset.",
      "asbval:note": "Exact match on dataset size and source.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-s13321-022-00613-8",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "metabolite-candidate-ranking-likelihood-scoring",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "parameters",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "SMRT dataset with 80,038 experimental retention times used for training",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T12:59:28.051672+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/metabolite-candidate-ranking-likelihood-scoring/009",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The most common approach to annotate metabolites is to query a metabolomics database for compounds that have a mass compatible with the experimental masses. Often this query returns multiple annotation candidates for the same mass. Next, the researcher tries to discard, or score according to plausibility, the candidate annotations using other molecule's properties.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper describes the exact use case: multiple candidates from mass search need to be ranked using additional properties like RT.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-s13321-022-00613-8",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "metabolite-candidate-ranking-likelihood-scoring",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Apply when you have query mass spectrum matched to multiple candidate metabolites and need to re-rank by retention time likelihood",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T12:59:28.051672+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/metabolite-candidate-ranking-likelihood-scoring/010",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Since laboratories usually customize the Chromatographic Method (CM) for the needs of each experiment, a SMRT-based model cannot be directly applied to experimental data from other laboratories, or even other experiments conducted in the same laboratory... To build such a projection function, a set of known molecules whos [sic] RTs is known in both CMs is needed.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper explicitly addresses the problem of different chromatographic methods and proposes the projection solution.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-s13321-022-00613-8",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
